							<br class="clear"/>
							<!-- End each blog post -->
							
														
							<div class="post_wrapper author">
								<div id="about_the_author">
									<div class="gravatar"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/anahebraflaster/"><img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/Hebra-Flaster_Headshot-2-100x100.jpeg" width="100" height="100" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/Hebra-Flaster_Headshot-2-300x300.jpeg 2x" alt="Ana Hebra Flaster" class="avatar avatar-100 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-100 alignnone photo" /></a></div>
									<div class="description author withsidebar">
										<h6><a href="https://lithub.com/author/anahebraflaster/">Ana Hebra Flaster</a></h6>
										Ana Hebra Flaster has written about Cuba and the Cuban American experience for national print and online media including <em>The Washington Post</em>, <em>The Wall Street Journal</em>, <em>The New York Times</em>, and <em>The Boston Globe</em>. Her commentaries and storytelling have aired on NPR and PBS’s Stories from the Stage. She is also the author of <em>Property of the Revolution: From a Cuban Barrio to a New Hampshire Mill Town</em>. She loves watching birds, walking in the woods, and chatting with just about anyone. After almost forty years in the Boston area, she recently moved back to southern New Hampshire with her husband, Andy, and their dogs, Luna and Beny.																			</div>
								</div><br class="clear"/><br/>
							</div>
							<br class="clear"/>
						</div>
					</div>
